  <P><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><B>Abstract:</B></font></P>
  <P><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">The \ghmst{h} problem is defined 
    as follows: given a set $S$ of points in the plane and $b\in S$, find a minimum-cost 
    spanning tree for $S$ rooted at $b$ with height at most $h$. We investigate 
    \emph{fast} and \emph{easy-to-implement} heuristics for the \ghmst{h} problem, 
    for any constant $h>0$, on instances obtained by choosing at random $n$ points 
    in a square of side length $L$. Firstly, we prove a general lower bound on 
    the solution cost. We introduce an easy-to-implement, very fast heuristic 
    and we prove that its solution cost matches the lower bound. We then analyze 
    three simple heuristics based on classical greedy algorithms (Prim's and Kruskal's 
    ones) for the MST problem. Rather surprisingly, they asymptotically do not 
    do better than the trivial heuristic that, regardless of $h$, connects all 
    points directly to the root. Indeed, we prove a tight lower bound $\Omega(L\cdot 
    n)$ that holds (with high probability) for the solution cost yielded by \emph{any} 
    of such three heuristics. Finally, all the studied heuristics have been implemented 
    and extensively tested over thousands of random instances. The numerical results 
    are discussed and compared with our theoretical results. </font></P>
